{\bf Referee report} on manuscript Ref:BO255, "Phaseshift equivalent $NN$
potentials and the deuteron" by A. Polls et al.

This work compares $S$ and $D$ wave matrix elements of kinetic and potential
energies of the deuteron for several phase-shift equivalent recent
potentials. The one-pion exchange important contributions are also examined.
Differences are attributed to off-shell differences.

This is an interesting study which should be published after authors have
considered the optimal remarks and revisions mentioned below.

0) The title says ``Phaseshift equivalent $NN$ potentials\ldots ``. It is
true that the quality of the reproduction of the $NN$ data is very good
($\chi ^2$ ~ 1 ) for all the 4 potentials in comparison. Nevertheless it could
well be that the $NN$ data (there could be for instance some differences in
the data sets in use to fit and calculate the $\chi ^2$) are not described in
exactly the same way. This could result in some, although presumably small,
differences in the phase shifts. Such comparison of phases is, I believe,
outside the size of this letter, however some comment about it could be
added and some of the differences shown in this work could be attributed to
this small on-shell differences?

1) It might be quite interesting to add in Table 1 a column giving the
$D/S = \eta $ ratio which has been measured experimentally. Looking at
results of Table 1 it seems that a small $P_D$ could be associated with a
small $V_{SD}$. We understand that the strength of the tensor force plays
here an important role, anything more?

2) It could be instructive to compare also the momentum distribution for the
$D$-wave of the deuteron, i.e. the equivalent of Eq. 2 and Fig. 1 but for
the $D$-wave.

3) For $V_{SD}$ in Fig. 2, the local $OPEP$ seems to be missing. Is there
really a $\delta$-function contribution to the tensor potential? None seems
to appear in any of the shown $V_{SD}$ matrix elements in Figs. 2, 3 and 4.
This is not the case for the $V_{SS}$ where matrix elements of different
potential can differ mainly through a $\delta$-function contribution. Such a
difference is explicitly illustrated in Fig. 2. In Fig. 3, the total Bonn V
and the Bonn $\pi, \rho$ $V_{SS}$ seems to differ mainly by a
$\delta$-function contribution. Any comment? This is also the case in Fig. 4
for the $V_{SS}$ of Argonne, Nijm1, Nijm2 and the low momentum part of Bonn.
It would be good if Authors could comment about it.

4) It seems that in Fig. 3 for $V_{SS}$ of Bonn, for $k \ge$ 800 MeV, the
$OPEP$ matrix element becomes very close to that of the total $V_{SS}$. Is
there any reason or is it just pure coincidence?

5) For an easier reading, authors could add in the upper left part of Fig.~3
the legend "Bonn" and in the upper right part the legend "Argonne" as it has
been done in the lower part.

6) For the same reason, a legend "$V_{SS}$" could be added in the left graph
of Fig. 4.

7) In most case ``Argonne'' has  been shortened in ``Argon'' in Table 1,
Figs. 1, 2 and 4. Authors could introduce this shortened notation. Nijm I
and Nijm II in the texte are denoted Nijm1 and Nijm2 in Figs. 1 and 4, it
will be better to have the same notation.

8) Ref. 7 has been published in Nucl. Phys. {\bf A627} (1997) 85.
Please check if Ref. 6 has been published. Ref. 10 should be "...Phys. Rev.
Lett. {\bf25} ..." and not "...Phys. Lett. {\bf 25}...".

\end{document}

