Re: Ms.# B0255
    "Phaseshift equivalent NN potentials and the deuteron"
By: A. Polls, H. Muther, R. Machleidt, M. Hjorth-Jensen

The authors examine the deuteron solutions of four modern phase-shift
equivalent potentials.  They notice the differences in the S- and D-wave
contributions to both the kinetic and potential energies and point out
there are some significant differences, even though the models produce
similar deuteron observables and nearly identical phase shifts.

I agree with most of the comments made here.  The one exception is the
paragraph following eq.(6).  Here the statement is made that the local
expression for OPE is not really justified.  However we have only on-shell
data to base such a decision on, and both the local and nonlocal models
fit that data, so I don't know what is meant here.  It is not obvious to me
that a heavy-meson-exchange theory necessarily gives a more accurate
representation of the complex QCD interactions that presumably underlie
the short-range NN interaction.  A few lines later the authors find it
remarkable that the Gaussian form factor used with the local OPE in the
Argonne model gives Vsd matrix elements like the nonlocal Bonn, which is
relying on rho-exchange and a much shorter-range form factor.  I think
maybe it isn't SO remarkable, again because they are fitting the same
on-shell data.  I realize the point of the paper is that there are
significant off-shell differences between the models, but I think they
can't be TOO big and still fit the data.  Finally at the end of this
paragraph the authors conclude "that even this long-range part of the NN
interaction is by no means settled."  But I think what is not settled is
how to handle the short-range behavior of OPE, which is not quite the
same thing.

My only other comment is that I think I already knew the content of the
paper, at least qualitatively, and I suspect most people interested in
the subject also know these things.  But it is probably worthwhile having
the detailed numbers in print so the amount of off-shell difference is
quantified.

Fig.2b appears to be missing the "local OPEP" curve.






